The problem asks to show that for an interior point $P$ of a triangle $ABC$, at least one of the angles $\angle PAB, \angle PBC, \angle PCA$ is at most $30^\circ$.

The proof proceeds by contradiction. Assume all three angles $\alpha = \angle PAB, \beta = \angle PBC, \gamma = \angle PCA$ are strictly greater than $30^\circ$. We use the trigonometric form of Ceva's theorem (or equivalent product identity for the sines of the angles) which states that
$$ \sin(A-\alpha)\sin(B-\beta)\sin(C-\gamma) = \sin\alpha\sin\beta\sin\gamma $$
where $A, B, C$ are the angles of the triangle.
We then use the inequality $\sin(A-\alpha) < 2\sin(A-30^\circ)\sin\alpha$ which holds when $\alpha > 30^\circ$.
Substituting this into the identity leads to $1 < 8 \sin(A-30^\circ)\sin(B-30^\circ)\sin(C-30^\circ)$.
The angles $A-30^\circ, B-30^\circ, C-30^\circ$ sum to $90^\circ$. By Jensen's inequality (or simple maximization), the product of sines is maximized when they are equal, giving a value of $(1/2)^3 = 1/8$. This yields $1 < 1$, a contradiction.

