The problem asks to show that for any triangle $ABC$ and interior point $P$, at least one of $\angle PAB, \angle PBC, \angle PCA$ is $\le 30^\circ$.
We proceed by contradiction, assuming all three angles are strictly greater than $30^\circ$.
We use the trigonometric form of Ceva's theorem (or equivalent product of sine rules) which implies:
$$ \sin(A - \alpha) \sin(B - \beta) \sin(C - \gamma) = \sin \alpha \sin \beta \sin \gamma $$
where $\alpha = \angle PAB, \beta = \angle PBC, \gamma = \angle PCA$.
Rearranging gives $\prod \frac{\sin(A - \alpha)}{\sin \alpha} = 1$.
We prove that for $\theta > 30^\circ$, $\frac{\sin(K - \theta)}{\sin \theta} < 2 \sin(K - 30^\circ)$.
Substituting this into the product leads to $1 < 8 \sin(A-30^\circ)\sin(B-30^\circ)\sin(C-30^\circ)$.
Using Jensen's inequality on $\ln(\sin x)$, the maximum of the RHS subject to sum of angles being $90^\circ$ is 1. This yields $1 < 1$, a contradiction.

